<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-dilations-virtual" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Virtual Tools for Dilations</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        In this section, we use virtual tools to perform dilations. We also 
        expand our definition of dilations to include negative scale factors.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <!--<subsection xml:id="subsec-dilations-virtual-scale">
    <title>How does the Scale Factor affect the Dilated Image?</title>
  -->
  <exploration xml:id="explore-sliding-scale">
    <title>Role of the Scale Factor</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use <xref ref="fig-vary-scale-factor"/> to complete the tasks
                in this exploration. This GeoGebra applet allows us to see how changing 
                the scale factor affects the dilation.
            </p>
        </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               With the slider for the scale factor set at <m>s=3</m>, 
               how is quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m> related to <m>ABCD</m>?
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-vary-scale-factor">
                <caption>
                    GeoGebra applet for <xref ref="explore-sliding-scale"/>
                </caption>
                <interactive xml:id="slide-scale-app"
                platform="geogebra">
                <slate surface="geogebra" material="qjarc5rc"/>
              </interactive>
            </figure>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the scale factor <m>s=1</m>? Why?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the slider is moved to <m>s=0</m>? Why do you
                think that happens?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the slider is moved to <m>s=\frac{-1}{2}</m> ?
                <m>s=-1</m> ? <m>s=-2</m> ? Describe the effect of a negative 
                scale factor on a dilation.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Construct the four lines, <m>\overleftrightarrow{EA}</m>,
                <m>\overleftrightarrow{EB}</m>, <m>\overleftrightarrow{EC}</m>,
                and <m>\overleftrightarrow{EA}</m>. What do you notice about 
                these lines and the image <m>A'B'C'D'</m> ? Is this also true 
                when you move the slider to other values, like <m>s=3</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                With <m>s=3</m>, use GeoGebra to measure the lengths <m>EA</m> and <m>EA'</m>,
                <m>EB</m> and <m>EB'</m>, <m>EC</m> and <m>EC'</m>, and 
                <m>ED</m> and <m>ED'</m>. What do you notice about these
                measurements?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Still with <m>s=3</m>, use GeoGebra to measure the four sides of the
                original quadrilateral, <m>AB</m>, <m>BC</m>,
                <m>CD</m>, and <m>DA</m>.Compare these to the measures of the four
                sides, <m>A'B'</m>, <m>B'C'</m>, <m>C'D'</m> and <m>D'A'</m> of 
                the dilated quadrilateral. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Measure the area of quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m> and its image 
                <m>A'B'C'D'</m>. Move the slider as helpful to determine how 
                the area of a figure is affected by the scale factor.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </exploration>
  
</section>